Hi, I'm assuming this channel is a way to connect to organizers / funding agency of NFAI, SPRIND. I wanted to discuss the requirements of the challenge and how it connects to the desired outcome. From the pitch I understood the desired outcome is to have EU capture more of AI value chain. Historical example would be: Germany benefited from building cars in the last hundred years.

Now the way NFAI is formulated is that by creating a frontier lab, with a unique technology that allows this new lab to make foundational models (or domain specific but significant) better than existing generation, EU would be at the forefront (frontier?) of AI progress.

But why might it work? Existing labs compete for talent agressively and are kind of competent in doing AI research, and have funding of many $B. There are bright computer scientists left in EU, although many top talents are already in Google Zurich / Deepmind / working in USA. But lets assume the talent is there and made available, like we find 10 groups x 5 people (2 scientists with great ideas + 2 engineers + leader) each.

## The nature of technology progress in CS

In this interview Jim Keller explains that Moore's law was in fact a bunch of stacked s-curves, and they keep coming up to form this kind of continuous progress from the outside https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=Nb2tebYAaOA. But some bits stay, like we keep working with silicon because too many inventions are made for it and pivoting would be not economical.